<p style="text-align:justify;">was displayed.  Here we were met by the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Borgne</span> who received us kindly and showed us into the tent<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  His women unsaddled our ho<span class="AddHand-editors">[rses]</span> took in our baggage and then prepared a plentiful meal of fresh Buffaloe of which we partook with a very good heart.  In the meantime the principal men among the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">schians</span> were busilly employed haranguing and encouraging their people to be kind to their new friends to call them into their tents, to guard their property, to give them plenty to eat, to barter with them on fair and equal terms<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  All this time the Borgne remained with us, made his company agreeable whenever he addressed us a Continual smile played upon his countenance but we had an oppertunity to observe that he treated his women more like slaves than like wives and they appeared in continual dread of him Which I am told is not without great reason for he can butcher them with the greatest composure imaginable.  Altho he is not of a jealous disposition he will not allow his wives to dispose of their favors without his consent<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  One of his Ladies on a late occasion when he was absent upon a hunting expedition thought proper to form a connex<span class="DelHand-author">t</span>ion with a Young man who took</p>
